commentBody:
@Vaer

My reply to you about the Hogan’s Heroes comment has been blocked three times. So I’m trying it as a new comment.

What about that song from the original Producers movie, from 1967, about springtime for that terrible German guy?

@john ezra
The question is, does reference to another less tragic or fraught piece of a place's history amount to an erasure of the tragic or to a revival of the place's larger history? 
When I say Dresden, do you think of delicate china or Allied carpet-bombing? What would a German say today? Can we hold two thoughts at once?

@Vaer

How about “Springtime for Hitler and Germany”?  Original movie, same era. 

Set in Hollywood, not a concentration camp.

@Vaer

But the original issue was whether NAGASAKI belonged in a puzzle that had a theme of innocuous words and phrases that happened to end in an explosive word. 

It seemed to me that that complaint was a nothing burger  others may disagree.

@The X-Phile
Just sing out a "Te Deum"
When you see that ICBM

@SP
You could hear my shriek from there, couldn't you?
Good one.  I read it to DHubby and he winced, writhed, and shook his head...

@Tom C.
Records used to be physical objects of various sizes.
What confuses the issue is the Grammys having separate awards for song, album, and record of the year, where by ' record' they mean big-selling single.

@Kyle
Off the record, it looks like you should read about records.
btw, which single won record of the year this year? Oh yeah, that would be the album "Luther".

@Francis
Music to my ears is to hear that you're still posting, which means breathing. How is the air up there?
One evening last week, the smoke was so thick in Detroit, I couldn't see the skyscrapers of downtown from my living room window. The next morning, I wore a KN95 mask on my commute to work, which helped. I dreamed of heading up north, where the air should be fresh and clean, but was, reportedly, worse.

@Bill
Yeah, well, there has been an order issued for Canada to keep its smoke North of the border, and fast.  Tariffs already in the works to enforce this demand.  Take that!!!

Also, the Tide is going to be ordered to ebb rather than flow today; film at 11.

@MOL
Yes, and I'm tired of hearing about the "Canadian wildfires"! Half of the Boundary Waters wildfire--which is the one most affecting Francis, and myself, and any of RiA's kinfolk still living in Iron Mountain--is in northern Minnesota, USA! That's why they call it "Boundary"!
Or, as my BFF Paul opined--"we all know it's a plot by Minnesota Lutherans to bring on Ragnarok."

@Mean Old Lady

Some people never fail to find a way to try to make a buck out of a bad situation.  

When I heard tariff policy was now based on weather patterns and wildfires, somehow I wasn't the least bit surprised.

@Andrzej

Sounds like Francis did watch TNG, just never got past it. Would agree if he didn’t it would be required for understanding the Cardassians, the Bajorans, the Maquis, the Ferengi, not to mention appreciating Worf and the O’Briens.

Speaking of O’Brien did anyone catch Colm Meaney in “Remarkably Bright Creatures” with Sally Field? So happy to see him again, one of the most under appreciated actors in all of Star Trek, I think.

@D

No, Daddio.

It's from the Jazz Age (30s-40s) when, if you were cool, you might be called a hepcat.

@Cathy King

It's not just song lyrics.  Many a female TikTok influencer has built their career on advice that is demeaning to women, leading their flock by example down regrettable avenues.   But the boys are catching up, with the manosphere looksmaxxing crapola, etc.

Science tells us that the human brain is not fully developed until age 25, roughly.  We often see anecdotal proof of this.

@Andrzej

And in contrast to NanuNanu, I think "trivet" is super common.  You can look in any online kitchen-supply catalog, from commercial to high-end consumer (like Williams-Sonoma) and find whole sections devoted to them.

Probably depends on how much time you spend in the kitchen.  I used to be a chef and all, so...

@CCNY

My wife and I eat sitting on the sofa - the dining table is where I do jigsaw puzzles so it's never available for, well, dining 🤣

(Ours is not a serious household)

@Andrzej
In our kitchen we have two metal trivets, although one, if not both (I'm not at home right now), have *four* little legs--and therefore should properly be called "quadrivets."
Very useful for cooling pies upon.

@CCNY

A trestle, of course, is what a train crosses a road or stream on; in my youth, I always confused it with trellis, which is what a vine climbs. 

I never had an issue with trivet.

@Times Rita
"Mommy, when I grow up, I want to be an Objectivist."
"Well, you'll have to choose one or the other."

@Times Rita
Ayn Rand is one of those authors young people admire because they feel impressed with themselves for having read something with so many pages.  A lot of conservatives admire her because of her disdain of altruism -- setting aside (or being ignorant of) her hatred of religion (Christianity in particular).

But the puzzle was pretty good.

@Lewis,
